{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488853"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:00:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:00:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"559"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/559"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.18,0.04,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102129"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/559"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84586"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1198"},{"type":"tags","id":"3376"},{"type":"tags","id":"3455"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35611"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102129"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of progressive difficulty swallowing. He has no significant medical history. He takes an over-the-counter medication for heartburn, which he has experienced for many years. He drinks three glasses of wine daily and has a 20 pack-year smoking history. His diet mainly consists of fast food. He consumes at least six cups of coffee per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn endoscopy five years ago showed low-grade oesophagitis. He describes significant stress in his office job. His wife reports that he has lost weight and is currently 75 kg, which concerns him as he has always been overweight. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. An endoscopy finds an adenocarcinoma of the distal oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following risk factors is most likely to have contributed to the development of this tumour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Barrett\u0027s oesophagus","Smoking","Alcohol consumption","Obesity","Drinking hot fluids"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, \u003Cstrong\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely risk factor for the development of the adenocarcinoma. While not explicitly stated in the stem, it is highly probable that this carcinoma developed in an area of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) leading to Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is the most significant predisposing risk factor for oesophageal adenocarcinoma. The patient\u0027s history of long-standing heartburn and previous low-grade oesophagitis supports this likelihood. Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is the major risk factor for adenocarcinoma of the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmoking\u003C/strong\u003E is a risk factor for both squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma of the oesophagus. However, Barrett\u0027s oesophagus remains the most important risk factor for oesophageal adenocarcinoma. The patient\u0027s 20 pack-year smoking history likely contributed to his risk, but to a lesser extent than Barrett\u0027s oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to GORD and consequently Barrett\u0027s oesophagus, but it is not directly the main risk factor for developing oesophageal adenocarcinoma. The patient\u0027s alcohol intake may have contributed to his GORD, indirectly increasing his risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E is an important risk factor for adenocarcinoma, but not as significant as Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. Individuals with obesity in the higher quartile for BMI have a 7.6-fold risk of developing oesophageal adenocarcinoma compared to those in the lower quartile. This patient has been overweight, but might not have been obese.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrinking hot fluids\u003C/strong\u003E is a risk factor more associated with squamous cell carcinoma in the proximal third of the oesophagus. This is less of a prominent risk factor in oesophageal adenocarcinoma, particularly given the distal location of this patient\u0027s tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn a global basis, oesophageal cancer is the eighth most common cancer, with squamous carcinomas being the majority. However, adenocarcinoma is the more common variant of oesophageal cancer in higher-income countries. The patient\u0027s constellation of risk factors, including chronic GORD, previous oesophagitis, and lifestyle factors, all likely contributed to the development of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus and subsequent adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is the most significant risk factor for the development of oesophageal adenocarcinoma.","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) is a major contributor to the development of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus.","Obesity, smoking, and alcohol consumption are additional risk factors for oesophageal adenocarcinoma, but less significant than Barrett\u0027s oesophagus."],"references":["Domper Arnal MJ, Ferr\u00e1ndez Arenas \u00c1, Lanas Arbeloa \u00c1. Esophageal cancer: Risk factors, screening and endoscopic treatment in Western and Eastern countries. World J Gastroenterol. 2015 Jul 14;21(26):7933-43. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26185366/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84586"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"559"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84586"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-08T15:53:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-08T15:54:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"559"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102129"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7